{"id":"cond-mat/0610722","submitter":"Yuri Gartstein","authors":"Yu.N. Gartstein, T.D. Bustamante, S. Ortega Castillo","title":"Nanotubes in polar media: polarons and excitons on a cylinder","comments":"Manuscript originally submitted on September 27, 2006","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.other cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":null,"abstract":"  Electrons and holes on semiconducting nanotubes immersed in sluggish polar\nmedia can undergo self-localization into polaronic states. We evaluate the\nbinding energy $\\bpol$ of adiabatic Fr\\\"{o}hlich-Pekar polarons confined to a\ncylindrical surface and compare it to the corresponding exciton binding energy\n$\\bexc$. The ratio $\\bpol/\\bexc$ is found to be a non-monotonic function of the\ncylinder radius $R$ that can reach values of about 0.35, substantially larger\nthan values of about 0.2 for 2$d$ or 3$d$ systems. We argue that these findings\nrepresent a more general crossover effect that could manifest itself in other\nsemiconductor nanostructures in 3$d$ polar environments. As a result of the\nstrong polaronic effect, the activation energy of exciton dissociation into\npolaron pairs is significantly reduced which may lead to enhanced charge\nseparation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 26 Oct 2006 03:16:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
